\b Everyone\rquote s essay should address the following requirements:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sl276\slmult1\b0\f2\'b7\tab\ul\f0 Purpose/Project:\ulnone   Your purpose is \i to explore and explain\i0  the background of the problem or issue you\rquote ve selected, in order to find the most appropriate ways to engage with and participate in the larger conversation about the problem or issue.  Your specific goal is to arrive at a question or series of questions for further scholarly research (topic proposal).\par
\pard\fi-360\li1440\sl276\slmult1\f3 o\tab\f0 When you \b aim\b0  to explore a topic, you don\rquote t start with a claim you want to prove, but with a question you want to answer.  At this stage, your question might still be pretty vague, such as \ldblquote What are the current proposals for reforming public schools in the U.S.?\rdblquote   or \ldblquote What can pop culture\rquote s obsession with zombies tell us about current cultural attitudes toward immigration?\rdblquote   (ok, that last one took me a few pre-questions to get to \f1 J\f0 ).  The best way to come to these questions is to start with real world problems.  Hopefully, you\rquote ve already looked at some news stories that have piqued your interest, events that can be framed as \b oppressions\b0 , complete with an oppressor, a victim, and an activist.  As we talked about in class, you should NOT already know the answer to your question when you get started.  More often than not, you need to do a little background reading before you can generate a useful question.\par
\pard\li1440\sl276\slmult1\par
